Load the libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(janitor)
library(here)
library(ggmap)

Load the Data

We will use two separate data sets for this homework.

  1. The first data set represent sightings of grizzly bears (Ursos arctos) in Alaska.

  2. The second data set is from Brandell, Ellen E (2021), Serological dataset and R code for: Patterns and processes of pathogen exposure in gray wolves across North America, Dryad, Dataset.

  3. Load the grizzly data and evaluate its structure. As part of this step, produce a summary that provides the range of latitude and longitude so you can build an appropriate bounding box.

grizzly<- read_csv(here("lab12", "data", "bear-sightings.csv"))

  1. Use the range of the latitude and longitude to build an appropriate bounding box for your map.
lati<- c(55.02, 70.37)
longi<- c(-166.2, -131.3)
bobox <- make_bbox(longi, lati, f = 0.05)
  1. Load a map from stamen in a terrain style projection and display the map.
mapter<- get_map(bobox, maptype = "terrain", source = "stamen")
## Map tiles by Stamen Design, under CC BY 3.0. Data by OpenStreetMap, under ODbL.
ggmap(mapter)

  1. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of grizzly bears in Alaska.
ggmap(mapter)+
  geom_point(data = grizzly, aes(longitude, latitude, alpha=0.1))+
  labs(title = "Grizzly Bear Sightings In Alaska",
       x= "Longitude",
       y= "Latitude")

9. Build a final map that overlays the recorded observations of wolves in the lower 48 states.

ggmap(mapterline) +
  geom_point(data = us_wolves, aes(long, lat))+
  labs(title = "Locations of Observed Wolves",
       x= "Longitude",
       y= "Latitude")

10. Use the map from #9 above, but add some aesthetics. Try to fill and color by population.

ggmap(mapterline) +
  geom_point(data = us_wolves, aes(long, lat, fill=pop, color=pop))+
  labs(title = "Locations of Observed Wolves",
       x= "Longitude",
       y= "Latitude")
